{"title_page": "Scrubtit", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| name = Scrubtit\n| image = Acanthornis magna - Myrtle Forest.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704585/0 |title=''Acanthornis magna'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Acanthornis\n| parent_authority = [[William Vincent Legge|Legge]], 1887\n| species = magna\n| authority = ([[John Gould|Gould]], 1855)\n| synonyms = ''Acanthornis magnus''\n}}\n\nThe '''scrubtit''' (''Acanthornis magna'') is a species of [[bird]] in the thornbill family [[Acanthizidae]]. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Tasmania]] and [[King Island (Tasmania)|King Island]] in [[Australia]]. Its natural [[habitat]] is the temperate [[rainforest]], ''[[Nothofagus]]'' beech forest and [[eucalypt]] woodland. It is a small species that resembles the ''[[Sericornis]]'' scrubwrens (with which it was once placed).\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe scrubtit belongs to the [[monotypic]] genus ''Acanthornis''.<ref>IOC-Classification: [http://www.worldbirdnames.org/n-lyrebirds.html Scrubtit (''Acanthornis magna''), Acanticidae in order Passeriformes]</ref> A 2017 genetic study using both mitochondrial and nuclear DNA found the ancestor of the scrubtit diverged from that of the three whitefaces of the genus ''[[Aphelocephala]]'' around 7 million years ago. The combined lineage had diverged from the thornbill lineage around 13 million years ago.<ref name=\"Marki 2017\">{{cite journal|author=Marki, Petter Z.; J\u00f8nsson, Knud A., Irestedt, Martin; Nguyen, Jacqueline M.T.; Rahbek, Carsten; Fjelds\u00e5, Jon |date=2017|title=Supermatrix phylogeny and biogeography of the Australasian Meliphagides radiation (Aves: Passeriformes)|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=107|pages=516\u201329|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2016.12.021|pmid=28017855|hdl=10852/65203|hdl-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe scrubtit is {{convert|11|to|12|cm|in|2}} long and weighs around {{convert|10|g|oz|2}}. The [[plumage]] consists of a white throat and belly, a brown back, crown, flank and tail, black wings and grey on the face. The eye is pale and the bill is short, black and slightly curved. The species is often silent but makes quite loud contact [[bird vocalization|calls]] and has a song described as \"sweet [and] musical\".\n\n==Behaviour==\nThe scrubtit forages individually, in pairs or in small family groups near the ground in dense cover. It feeds on small invertebrates, particularly insects and their eggs. The species will associate with [[mixed-species feeding flock]]s. The species is territorial and [[monogamy|monogamous]], with the breeding season lasting from September to January. The nest is a woven globe with a side entrance, lined with feathers and fur, camouflaged and usually found between 1\u20133 m off the ground. The [[avian clutch size|clutch size]] is usually three eggs but sometimes four. The eggs measure {{convert|18 x 15 mm|in}} and are pearly white, with fine reddish spots, mostly around the larger end.<ref>Morcombe, Michael (2012) Field Guide to Australian Birds. Pascal Press, Glebe, NSW. Revised edition. ISBN 978174021417-9</ref> No information exists about [[avian incubation|incubation]] or nestling times. Both parents feed the chicks in the nest, but unlike many Australian passerines [[helpers at the nest|helpers]] have never been reported.<ref>See for instance [http://www.tau.ac.il/lifesci/zoology/members/yom-tov/articles/Old_endemics.pdf Old endemics and new invaders: alternative strategies of passerines for living in the Australian environment]</ref> The species is victim to [[brood parasitism]] by [[fan-tailed cuckoo]]s (''Cacomantis flabelliformis'') and [[shining bronze-cuckoo]]s (''Chrysococcyx lucidus''), and [[quoll]]s (''Dasyurus'') also take eggs and nestlings.<ref>Gregory, P. (2020). \"Scrubtit (Acanthornis magna), version 1.0.\" In ''Birds of the World'' (J. del Hoyo, A. Elliott, J. Sargatal, D. A. Christie, and E. de Juana, Editors). Cornell Lab of Ornithology, Ithaca, NY, USA. https://doi.org/10.2173/bow.scrubt2.01</ref>\n\nThe species has a restricted range but is not considered [[threatened]] by the [[IUCN]]. The subspecies found on King Island is considered [[critically endangered]], however. The species is shy and unobtrusive and is seldom observed by people.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n* Del Hoyo, J.; Elliot, A. & Christie D. (editors). (2006). Handbook of the Birds of the World. Volume 12: Picathartes to Tits and Chickadees. Lynx Edicions. {{ISBN|978-84-96553-42-2}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1586082}}\n\n[[Category:Acanthizidae]]\n[[Category:Birds of Tasmania]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1855]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Tasmania]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| name = Scrubtit\n| image = Acanthornis magna - Myrtle Forest.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704585/0 |title=''Acanthornis magna'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Acanthornis\n| parent_authority = [[William Vincent Legge|Legge]], 1887\n| species = magna\n| authority = ([[John Gould|Gould]], 1855)\n| synonyms = ''Acanthornis magnus''\n}}\n\nThe '''scrubtit''' (''Acanthornis magna'') is a species of [[bird]] in the thornbill family [[Acanthizidae]]. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Tasmania]] and [[King Island (Tasmania)|King Island]] in [[Australia]]. Its natural [[habitat]] is the temperate [[rainforest]], ''[[Nothofagus]]'' beech forest and [[eucalypt]] woodland. It is a small species that resembles the ''[[Sericornis]]'' scrubwrens (with which it was once placed).\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe scrubtit belongs to the [[monotypic]] genus ''Acanthornis''.<ref>IOC-Classification: [http://www.worldbirdnames.org/n-lyrebirds.html Scrubtit (''Acanthornis magna''), Acanticidae in order Passeriformes]</ref> A 2017 genetic study using both mitochondrial and nuclear DNA found the ancestor of the scrubtit diverged from that of the three whitefaces of the genus ''[[Aphelocephala]]'' around 7 million years ago. The combined lineage had diverged from the thornbill lineage around 13 million years ago.<ref name=\"Marki 2017\">{{cite journal|author=Marki, Petter Z.; J\u00f8nsson, Knud A., Irestedt, Martin; Nguyen, Jacqueline M.T.; Rahbek, Carsten; Fjelds\u00e5, Jon |date=2017|title=Supermatrix phylogeny and biogeography of the Australasian Meliphagides radiation (Aves: Passeriformes)|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=107|pages=516\u201329|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2016.12.021|pmid=28017855|hdl=10852/65203|hdl-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe scrubtit is {{convert|11|to|12|cm|in|2}} long and weighs around {{convert|10|g|oz|2}}. The [[plumage]] consists of a white throat and belly, a brown back, crown, flank and tail, black wings and grey on the face. The eye is pale and the bill is short, black and slightly curved. The species is often silent but makes quite loud contact [[bird vocalization|calls]] and has a song described as \"sweet [and] musical\".\n\n==Behaviour==\nThe scrubtit forages individually, in pairs or in small family groups near the ground in dense cover. It feeds on small invertebrates, particularly insects and their eggs. The species will associate with [[mixed-species feeding flock]]s. The species is territorial and [[monogamy|monogamous]], with the breeding season lasting from September to January. The nest is a woven globe with a side entrance, lined with feathers and fur, camouflaged and usually found between 1\u20133 m off the ground. The [[avian clutch size|clutch size]] is usually three eggs but sometimes four, although no information exists about [[avian incubation|incubation]] or nestling times. Both parents feed the chicks in the nest, but unlike many Australian passerines [[helpers at the nest|helpers]] have never been reported.<ref>See for instance [http://www.tau.ac.il/lifesci/zoology/members/yom-tov/articles/Old_endemics.pdf Old endemics and new invaders: alternative strategies of passerines for living in the Australian environment]</ref> The species is victim to [[brood parasitism]] by [[fan-tailed cuckoo]]s (''Cacomantis flabelliformis'') and [[shining bronze-cuckoo]]s (''Chrysococcyx lucidus''), and [[quoll]]s (''Dasyurus'') also take eggs and nestlings.<ref>Gregory, P. (2020). \"Scrubtit (Acanthornis magna), version 1.0.\" In ''Birds of the World'' (J. del Hoyo, A. Elliott, J. Sargatal, D. A. Christie, and E. de Juana, Editors). Cornell Lab of Ornithology, Ithaca, NY, USA. https://doi.org/10.2173/bow.scrubt2.01</ref>\n\nThe species has a restricted range but is not considered [[threatened]] by the [[IUCN]]. The subspecies found on King Island is considered [[critically endangered]], however. The species is shy and unobtrusive and is seldom observed by people.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n* Del Hoyo, J.; Elliot, A. & Christie D. (editors). (2006). Handbook of the Birds of the World. Volume 12: Picathartes to Tits and Chickadees. Lynx Edicions. {{ISBN|978-84-96553-42-2}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1586082}}\n\n[[Category:Acanthizidae]]\n[[Category:Birds of Tasmania]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1855]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Tasmania]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBehaviour:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scrubtit"}
{"title_page": "Tim O'Brien (illustrator)", "text_new": "{{For|others named Tim O'Brien|Tim O'Brien (disambiguation){{!}}Tim O'Brien}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name        = Tim O'Brien\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age |1964|11|16|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[New Haven, Connecticut]], U.S.\n| nationality   = American\n| training    = [[Paier College of Art]]\n| field  = [[illustration]], [[fine artist]]\n| awards        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Hamilton King Award]], 2009\n* Medals, Society of Illustrators, Graphis, The Art Directors Club, Society of Publication Designers\n}}\n| website = {{url|obrienillustration.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Tim O'Brien''' (born November 16, 1964) is an American artist who works in a [[Realism (arts)|realistic]] style.\n\nHis illustrations have appeared on the covers and interior pages of magazines such as ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', ''[[GQ]]'', ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', ''[[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]]'', ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', and many others. His illustrations are also used by the [[US Postal Service]] for [[postage stamps]].<ref name=\"uarts\" />\n\n==Early life and education==\nO'Brien's [[paternal]] grandparents came from Ireland, and his [[maternal]] grandparents from [[Norwich, Connecticut]], arriving in the United States from Quebec.<ref name=\"AIAP\" /> His grandfather became a caretaker at [[Yale University]].<ref name=\"shapiro\" />\n\nThe artist was the second of three boys in his family.<ref name=\"shapiro\" /> A youth officer suggested [[boxing]] and O'Brien took the advice and began training as a boxer in high school, going on to box as a [[Middleweight#Boxing|middleweight]] amateur in the [[Police Athletic League]].<ref name=\"shapiro\" /><ref name=\"nonslick\">{{cite web | first=Pete | last=Ryan | title=Tim O'Brien Interview | date=2010-03-29 | url =http://nonslick.blogspot.com/2010/03/tim-obrien.html |  accessdate = 2016-10-16 }}</ref> Although he drew and painted all during his youth, O'Brien thought that he would be a boxer.<ref name=\"shapiro\" />\n\nAt the age of 18, O'Brien gave up his ambitions of becoming a professional boxer and in the same year received a [[Pell Grant]] which he used to enroll in the [[Paier College of Art]],<ref name=\"shapiro\">{{cite news|last1=Shapiro|first1=Ellen|title=Tim O'Brien, Master Portrait Painter|url=http://buglogic.com/shapiro/Tim_O'Brien_Profile.html |accessdate=2016-10-17|issue=July\u2013August 2002|publisher=Communication Arts}}</ref> New Haven, CT.\n\nHe went on to graduate in 1987 with a [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] degree. His instructors at Paier included [[Leonard Everett Fisher]], [[Ken Davies (artist)|Ken Davies]] and Robert Zappalorti. While attending Paier, the young artist painted [[trompe l'oeil]] images for fun, which his instructors Ken Davies and Robert Zappalorti were also known to do, in which the viewer of the paintings are deceived into thinking they were seeing an actual object. In one such case, students attempted to use electrical outlets that O'Brien had painted on the wall.<ref name=\"shapiro\" /><ref name=\"North Haven News\" />\n\n===Artistic influences===\nIn grade school, O'Brien often visited the [[Yale University Art Gallery|Yale Art Gallery]].<ref name=\"shapiro\" /> O'Brien's favorite art works at this early age, which he was able to view at the Yale Gallery, were by [[Thomas Eakins]] and [[Paul Cadmus]], of which the young artist especially admired the detail and brushwork of Cadmus.<ref name=\"shapiro\" /> Other early influences for the artist were the 19th century Russian painter, [[Ivan Shishkin]], and British painter, [[Lord Leighton]].<ref name=\"lines and colors\">{{cite web|last1=Parker|first1=Charley|title=Tim O'Brien|url=http://linesandcolors.com/2006/09/15/tim-obrien/|website=Lines and Color|accessdate=2016-10-28}}</ref> Later influences for O'Brien include various contemporary artists such as [[Gottfried Helnwein]], [[George Tooker]] and [[Mark Tansey]], as well as illustrators such as [[Guy Billout]] and [[David Suter]].<ref name=\"AIAP\" />\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early===\nBefore graduation from Paier in 1987, O'Brien entered into what became a long relationship with the artists' representative [[Peter Lott]]. Lott had seen O'Brien's work at the [[Society of Illustrators]] Student Show.<ref name=\"shapiro\" />\n\nO'Brien started his illustration career primarily as a book cover artist<ref name=\"AIAP\">{{cite web|last1=Newman|first1=Robert|title=Illustrator Profile: Tim O'Brien|url=http://www.ai-ap.com/publications/article/13942/illustrator-profile-tim-obrien-focus-on-ideas.html|website=AI-IP|accessdate=2016-10-05}}</ref> and continues to work for book publishing houses, creating covers for such authors as [[Ray Bradbury]], [[Thomas Hardy]], [[Walter Dean Myers]] and many others.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tim O'Brien|url=https://www.librarything.com/author/obrientim-14&all=1|website=Library Thing|accessdate=2016-10-30}}</ref>\n\nThe artist credits his first big break as a ''Time'' Magazine cover done in 1989.<ref name=\"AIAP\" /> Even though O'Brien's contribution to the cover was only a painting of a small teardrop overlaid on a [[Gilbert Stewart]] portrait of [[George Washington]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Time Magazine, Oct 23 1989|url=http://content.time.com/time/covers/0,16641,19891023,00.html|website=Time Magazine|accessdate=2016-10-05}}</ref> it got him the attention of magazine art directors, and bigger assignments quickly followed.<ref name=\"AIAP\" /> O'Brien was called on again almost 20 years later to paint another teardrop on the cover of ''Time'', for the cover story \"The Price Of Greed\" following the onset of [[the great recession|a severe global financial recession]] in the September 29, 2008 issue of the magazine.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Price of Greed|url=http://content.time.com/time/covers/europe/0,16641,20080929,00.html|website=Time Magazine|accessdate=2016-10-05}}</ref>\n\n==Notable works==\n\n===Book covers===\n\nBetween 2008 and 2010, O'Brien was commissioned by [[Scholastic Publishing]] to illustrate each cover of ''[[The Hunger Games]]'' trilogy, by [[Suzanne Collins]], including ''The Hunger Games'' \"mockingjay\" logo. The images were then used again for promotional posters when the film distributor [[Lionsgate]] turned the best selling books into a film franchise.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Aronoff|first1=Amy|title=Professor Tim O'Brien Swept Up In Hunger Games Success As Logo Becomes Ubiquitous|url=http://gateway.pratt.edu/top-stories-apr-2012/2012/4/18/professor-tim-obrien-swept-up-in-hunger-games-success-as-log.html|website=Pratt|publisher=Pratt Institute|accessdate=2016-10-05}}</ref> At the end of the films official [[theatrical trailer]], the ring and bird by the artist are seen ablaze.\n\nO'Brien closely collaborated on the designs with his wife, Elizabeth Parisi, Creative Director for Scholastic, Inc.<ref name=\"NYDN\">{{cite web|last1=Weichselbaum|first1=Simone|title=Wings of love: 'Hunger Games' logo is brainchild of Brooklyn couple|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/wings-love-hunger-games-logo-brainchild-brooklyn-couple-article-1.1060947|website=New York Daily News|accessdate=2016-10-06}}</ref>\n\n===''Time'' covers===\nTime Magazine covers by the artist are in the [[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]] of the [[Smithsonian]]<ref name=\"NGA\">{{cite web|title=Time Magazine Collection|url=http://npg.si.edu/portraits/collection-highlights/time-magazine-highlights?page=8&edan_q=*%3A*&edan_fq%5B0%5D=date%3A%221990s%22&edan_fq%5B1%5D=online_media_type%3A%22Images%22|website=National Portrait Gallery|publisher=Smithsonian|accessdate=2016-10-06}}</ref>\n\nStarting in 1989, O'Brien worked with [[art director]], Arthur Hochstein, and created over a dozen covers for ''Time'' with him. Other art directors at Time that the artist has worked closely with are Joe Zeff and D.W. Pine.<ref name=\"spd\">{{cite web|last1=Newman|first1=Robert|title=The Time Covers of Arthur Hochstein, Pt. 1: Tim O'Brien|url=http://www.spd.org/2010/10/the.php|website=Society of Publication Designers|accessdate=2016-10-11}}</ref>\n\nO'Brien occasionally creates cover illustrations for ''Time'' Magazine that are a possibility for publication but never used, as was the case with his ''[[Time Person of the Year|Person of the Year]]'' (2007) portrait, in which the artist was commissioned to paint [[Vladimir Putin]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stengal|first1=Richard|title=The Covers You Don't See|url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/2007/article/0,28804,1699115_1699118_1699122,00.html?iid=sr-link5|website=Time Magazine|accessdate=2016-10-05}}</ref> Putin was selected as \"person of the year\" by ''Time'' in 2007, however the final image the magazine selected was a photograph by [[Platon (photographer)|Platon]].\n\nO'Brien's ''The End of Bin Laden'' cover, which the artist created in 2002 when editors at ''Time'' believed the [[Osama bin Laden|al-Qaeda leader]] was trapped and was or would soon be dead in Afghanistan,<ref name=\"North Haven News\" /> was not published until nine years later in the May 20, 2011 issue.<ref name=\"AIAP\" /> In the case of ''The End of Bin Laden'' cover image, O'Brien employed a concept that had been used much earlier by ''Time'' in which is a red X is painted over the portrait. The first time this concept was used was for Adolf Hitler in the May 7, 1945 issue of the magazine, before Hitler's body was discovered.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gustini|first1=Ray|title=A Brief History of Time Magazine's X Covers|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2011/05/brief-history-time-magazine-red-x-covers/350228/|website=The Atlantic|accessdate=2016-11-02}}</ref> O'Brien had used the same red X approach for an earlier ''Time'' cover, ''The Death of Abu Mousab al-Zarqawi'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/covers/0,16641,20060619,00.html |title=TIME Magazine Cover: The Death of Abu Mousab al-Zarqawi - June 19, 2006 - Iraq - Al-Qaeda - Terrorism |publisher=Content.time.com |date=2006-06-19 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref> for the June 19, 2006 issue of the magazine.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rothman|first1=Lily|title=Behind the Osama bin Laden 'Red X' TIME Cover|url=http://time.com/4307301/5-years-osama-bin-laden/|website=Time Magazine|accessdate=2016-11-02}}</ref>\nAs of 2020, Tim O'Brien has had over 30 Time covers published.\nListed below are a selection of notable works for ''Time'' by the artist.\n\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n*September 4, 1996 ''The Choice''<ref>{{cite web|author=posted by Robert Newman |url=http://www.spd.org/2010/10/the.php |title=The Time Covers of Arthur Hochstein, Pt. 1: Tim O'Brien - Grids - SPD.ORG - Grids |publisher=Spd.Org |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*December 28, 1998 ''Men of the Year, Kenneth Star and Bill Clinton''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/covers/0,16641,19981228,00.html |title=TIME Magazine Cover: Kenneth Starr & Bill Clinton, Men of the Year - Dec. 28, 1998 - Bill Clinton - Kenneth Starr - Person of the Year - U.S. Presidents - Scandals |publisher=Content.time.com |date=1998-12-28 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*March 10, 2003 ''Life After Saddam''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/covers/0,16641,20030310,00.html |title=TIME Magazine Cover: Saddam Hussein - Mar. 10, 2003 - Saddam Hussein - Iraq - Middle East |publisher=Content.time.com |date=2003-03-10 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*November 10, 2008 ''The Choice''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/0,9263,7601081110,00.html |title=TIME Magazine - U.S. Edition - November 10, 2008 Vol. 172 No. 19 |publisher=Content.time.com |date=2008-11-10 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n{{Col-2}}\n*June 7, 2010 ''Why Being Pope Means Never Having to Say You're Sorry''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/pacific/0,9263,503100607,00.html |title=TIME Magazine - South Pacific Edition - June 7, 2010 No. 22 |publisher=Content.time.com |date=2010-06-07 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*December 20, 2010 ''Palin in Progress''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/covers/0,16641,20101220,00.html |title=TIME Magazine Cover: Palin in Progress - Dec. 20, 2010 - Sarah Palin - Republicans - Politics |publisher=Content.time.com |date=2010-12-20 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*May 20, 2011 ''The End of Bin Laden''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/covers/0,16641,20110520,00.html |title=TIME Magazine Cover: The End of Bin Laden - May 20, 2011 - Al-Qaeda - Osama bin Laden - Terrorism - Special Issues |publisher=Content.time.com |date=2011-05-20 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*September 5, 2011 ''The World After Gaddafi''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/0,9263,7601110905,00.html?iid=sr-link7 |title=TIME Magazine - U.S. Edition - September 5, 2011 Vol. 178 No. 9 |publisher=Content.time.com |date=2011-09-05 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n{{Col-end}}\n\n===''Rolling Stone''===\nO'Brien illustrated portraits of [[The Police]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Stone |first=Rolling |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/100-greatest-artists-of-all-time-19691231/the-police-20110420 |title=The Police &#124; 100 Greatest Artists |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=2010-12-02 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref> [[Michael Jackson]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://illoz.com/obrien/?section=portfolios&gallery_id=12&image_id=19933&search_id=2015&search_type=image |title=Tim O'Brien - Portraits and Illustrations |publisher=Illoz.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref> [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Stone |first=Rolling |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/100-greatest-artists-of-all-time-19691231/nirvana-20110926 |title=Nirvana &#124; 100 Greatest Artists |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=2010-12-02 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref> and [[Little Richard]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://illoz.com/obrien/?section=portfolios&gallery_id=12&image_id=395&search_id=10365 |title=Tim O'Brien - Portraits and Illustrations |publisher=Illoz.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref> in ''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s 100 Greatest Artists of All Time<ref>{{cite web|title=Rolling Stone: The 100 Greatest Artists of All Time|url=http://www.spd.org/2011/04/rolling-stone-the-100-greatest.php|website=Society of Publication Designers|accessdate=2016-10-06}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, O'Brien said the work he was most proud of was his 2008 cover illustration for ''Rolling Stone'' in which the magazine endorsed candidate Barack Obama for President.<ref name=\"NYDN\" /> The cover, which depicted the future President with a halo-like glow around him, created a mild controversy, with critics of the image saying it [[deification|deified]] the candidate.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=Michael Orion|title=The Deification of Obama|url=http://mopowell.blogspot.com/2008/03/deification-of-obama.html|accessdate=2016-10-30}}</ref>\n\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n'''Covers'''\n*March 2008 Cover, ''Barack Obama, A New Hope''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/coverwall/2008#1048 |title=2008 Magazine Archives |publisher=Rolling Stone |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*January 2009 Cover, ''Bush Apologizes''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/coverwall/2009#1070 |title=2009 Magazine Archives |publisher=Rolling Stone |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*February 2012 Cover, ''The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/coverwall/2012#1149 |title=2012 Magazine Archives |publisher=Rolling Stone |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n{{Col-2}}\n'''Page illustrations'''\n*''Al Gore:The Revolution is beginning'', June 28, 2007<ref>{{cite web|last=Bates |first=Eric |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/al-gore-the-revolution-is-beginning-20070628 |title=Al Gore's Movement to Stop Global Warming: 'The Revolution Is Beginning' |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=2007-06-28 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*''Beck'', March 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theispot.com/whatsnew/2014/3/tim-o-brien-beck-for-rolling-stone.htm |title=Tim O\u2019Brien: Beck for Rolling Stone |publisher=Theispot.com |date=2014-03-04 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n{{Col-end}}\n\n===''Mother Jones''===\nFor the December 2012 release, the magazine printed double covers, in which one cover was sent to [[subscribers]] of the magazine and the alternate cover was shown on [[newsstand]]s. O'Brien illustrated both covers, and in very different stylistic ways.<ref>{{cite web|author=Robert Newman |url=http://www.foliomag.com/behind-mother-jones-s-recent-dual-cover-strategy/#.UHxWIBh5nV0 |title=Behind Mother Jones\u2019s Recent Dual Cover Strategy - Folio: |publisher=Foliomag.com |date=2012-10-12 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref> For the cover that went to newsstands, titled ''Sugar Kills'', the artist created a surreal vignette of a glass pitcher as a human skull, and for the version delivered to subscribers, titled ''Solitary in Iran'', O'Brien painted a lonely jail cell with a single occupant. That both covers were illustrated by O'Brien was more by chance than design. The ''Mother Jones'' creative director Tim J. Luddy first completed conceptual sketches for both covers and after doing so, decided O'Brien was the best choice for both.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Newman|first1=Robert|title=Behind Mother Jones's Recent Dual Cover Strategy|url=http://www.foliomag.com/behind-mother-jones-s-recent-dual-cover-strategy/#.UHxWIBh5nV0|website=Folio|accessdate=2016-10-06}}</ref>\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n'''Covers'''\n*February 2008 ''The Last Empire''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://drawger.com/tonka/?article_id=4998 |title=Tim OBrien - The Last Empire |publisher=Drawger.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*September 2010, ''The BP Coverup''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/environment/2010/09/bp-ocean-cover-up |title=The BP Cover-Up \u2013 Mother Jones |publisher=Motherjones.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*March 2011, ''The Vampire Economy''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coverjunkie.com/new-covers/4651 |title=Coverjunkie |publisher=Coverjunkie |date=2016-10-31 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*July 2013, ''Gagged by Big Ag''<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.spd.org/2013/11/mother-jones-covers-designed-b.php |title=\"Namaste\" to Tim J Luddy of Mother Jones - Grids - SPD.ORG - Grids |publisher=Spd.Org |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*\n{{Col-2}}\n'''Page illustrations'''\n*''Harpy, Hero, Heretic: Hillary'', January 2007<ref>{{cite web|author=Jack Hitt |url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2007/01/harpy-hero-heretic-hillary |title=Harpy, Hero, Heretic: Hillary \u2013 Mother Jones |publisher=Motherjones.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n{{Col-end}}\n\n===Magazine work===\nO'Brien magazine covers have received numerous awards and citations including ''Cover of the Day'' by the Society of Publication Designers. Below are listed a small sample of noted cover illustrations by the artist.\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n*''[[The Atlantic]]'', April 2001, ''The Next Ruling Class''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/past/docs/issues/2001/04/bgcover.htm |title=Apr 2001 &#124; Cover Art &#124; O'Brien |publisher=The Atlantic |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*[[Smithsonian (magazine)|''Smithsonian'']], March 2012, ''100th Anniversary of The Titantic''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theispot.com/whatsnew/2012/4/tim-o-brien-the-titanic-for-smithsonian.htm |title=Tim O\u2019Brien: The Titanic for Smithsonian |publisher=Theispot.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', March 2011, ''Roger Goodell Throne of Games''<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.spd.org/2013/03/cover-of-the-day-friday-editio-38.php |title=Cover of the Day: Friday Edition - Grids - SPD.ORG - Grids |publisher=Spd.Org |date=2013-03-11 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n{{Col-2}}\n*''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', May 16, 2016, ''Vin Scully''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidesocal.com/dodgers/2016/05/10/vin-scully-is-sports-illustrateds-latest-cover-boy/ |title=Vin Scully is Sports Illustrated\u2019s latest cover boy. &#124; Inside the Dodgers |publisher=Insidesocal.com |date=2016-05-10 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*''[[GQ]]'', July 2015, ''Who is Mitt Romney?''<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.gq.com/story/mitt-romney-wells-tower-gq-august-2012 |title=Mitt Romney: Desperately Seeking Mitt |publisher=GQ |date=2012-07-24 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*''[[GQ]]'', January 2016, ''What Would Cool Jesus Do?''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theispot.com/whatsnew/2016/1/tim-o-brien-illustration-cool-jesus.htm |title=Tim O\u2019Brien Illustration: Cool Jesus |publisher=Theispot.com |date=2016-01-06 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n{{Col-end}}\n\n===Postage stamps===\nO'Brien's work first appeared on [[Postage stamps and postal history of the United States|U.S. postage stamps]] in 2006. The artist was commissioned to portray [[Hattie McDaniel]] as part of the U.S. Postal Services Black Heritage stamp series.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hattie McDaniel|url=http://postalmuseum.si.edu/tt/artwork/25/|website=Postal Museum|accessdate=2016-10-30}}</ref> The choice of the actress to be featured in this series of stamps which had included prominent figures in [[civil rights]] history such as [[Harriet Tubman]] and [[Martin Luther King, Jr]] caused some to voice concerns<ref>{{cite web|last1=Washington|first1=Robin|title=A Hattie McDaniel U.S. Mail Stamp?|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5306369|website=NPR News|publisher=National Public Radio|accessdate=2016-10-30}}</ref> The U.S. Postal Service defended their decision by noting that the actress was the first African American to Win an [[Academy Award]] as well as a being an influential civil rights advocate during the 1940s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hattie McDaniel|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/hattie-mcdaniel-first-african-american-to-win-an-academy-awardr-featured-on-new-39-cent-postage-stamp-55101272.html|website=PR NewsWire|publisher=US Postal Service|accessdate=2016-10-30}}</ref>\n\nUS postage stamps by O'Brien that followed:\n*[[Judy Garland]], 2006<ref>{{cite web|url=http://postalmuseum.si.edu/tt/artwork/21/ |title=Artwork - Trailblazers and Trendsetters - Art of the Stamp |publisher=Postalmuseum.si.edu |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*[[Danny Thomas]], 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=http://about.usps.com/postal-bulletin/2012/pb22328/html/info_026.htm |title=Stamp Announcement 12-18: Danny Thomas |publisher=About.usps.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*[[Shirley Temple]], 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=https://about.usps.com/news/national-releases/2016/pr16_027.htm |title=Shirley Temple Becomes the 20th Inductee in the Legends of Hollywood Stamp Series |publisher=About.usps.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*[[Father Theodore Hesburgh]], 2017 release<ref>{{cite web|url=http://about.usps.com/news/national-releases/2016/pr16_072.htm |title=USPS previews 2017 stamps |publisher=About.usps.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n\n==Working process==\nO'Brien begins with a detailed drawing on [[gesso|gessoed panel]], working on [[Sepia (color)|sepia]] or grey half tone and drawing with pencil, charcoal pencil, colored pencil, [[gouache]]. When this is completed the artist uses an [[airbrush]] to even tones and set the key of the artwork and add light and dark to areas. Then an [[Acrylic paint|acrylic]] coat is applied to the drawing and finally painted over in thin layers of oil.<ref name=\"modern met\">{{cite web|last1=Hosmer|first1=Katie|title=Incredibly Surreal Illustrations by Tim O'Brien|url=http://www.mymodernmet.com/profiles/blogs/tim-o-brien-conceptual-illustrations|website=My Modern Met|accessdate=2016-10-06}}</ref> Although the artist began illustrating well before personal computers were able to render complex images, some of his concept images are currently rendered using computer software.<ref name=\"AIAP\" />\n\n===Deadlines===\nThe turn-around time between an illustration being commissioned by a weekly magazine such as ''Time'' is often less than 48 hours from concept sketch to final art for the artist. During this time, the sketch or draft of the idea is the most demanding.<ref name=\"North Haven News\">{{cite web|last1=Bellmore|first1=Miichael|title=North Haven native works quietly, but images stay with us forever|url=http://www.nhregister.com/article/NH/20130202/NEWS/302029964|website=New Haven Register|accessdate=2016-10-17}}</ref>\n\nArthur Hockstein, art director at ''Time'' Magazine from 1994 through 2009<ref>{{cite web|last1=Newman|first1=Robert|title=Arthur Hochstein's 15 Favorite Time Magazine Covers|url=http://www.spd.org/2010/08/arthur-hochsteins-time-magazin.php|website=Society of Publication Designers|accessdate=2016-10-30}}</ref> said of O'Brien that the magazine staff was amazed at the intricacy and draftsmanship of O'Brien's work, delivered under such short deadlines.<ref name=\"shapiro\" /> Robert Newman, former Design Director at [[Entertainment Weekly]] recounted the paintings still being wet, delivered in specially constructed boxes containing the art by O'Brien and the smell of oil paint filling the room as the work was opened just before [[time unit|deadline]].<ref name=\"AIAP\" />\n\n===Creative process===\nO'Brien has said that he thinks of his paintings as one frame movies and his job as illustrator is to direct the viewer to see the idea when he wants them to see it.<ref name=\"The Day\">{{cite web|last1=Koster|first1=Rick|title=Illustrator Tim O'Brien to visit LACFA|url=http://www.theday.com/article/20131017/ENT16/310179606/-1/rss05|website=The Day|accessdate=2016-10-17}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview conducted by The Illustrators Guild of Ireland in 2002, O'Brien described his style by saying, \"My description is conceptual realism with a leaning toward the slightly idealized.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.illustratorsireland.com/index.php/features/fullstory/tim_obrien_interview/ |title=Illustrators Ireland: Features |accessdate=2008-05-17 |last=Byrne |first=Tom |date=2002-03-29 |work=Illustrators Guild of Ireland |publisher=Illustrators Ireland }}</ref>\n\n==Honors and service==\n\n===Honors===\nOn April 26, 2016 O'Brien spoke at the United Nations in New York City at the invitation of [[World Intellectual Property Organization|The World Intellectual Property Organization]], during which the artist's work were shown. He discussed [[commercial art]] and [[Intellectual property#Copyright infringement|intellectual property rights]] in a digital world and how technology is having both advantageous and troubling consequences on both.<ref name=\"UN\">{{cite web|title=Tim O'Brien Speaks at the United Nations on a pane;; titled ''Digital Creativity: Reimagining Culture For Sustainable Development''|url=https://altpick.com/news/10317|website=Alternative Pick|accessdate=2016-10-16}}</ref>\n* [[Hamilton King Award]], [[Society of Illustrators]] (2009)<ref name=\"soi\">{{cite web|title=Hamilton King 2009|url=https://www.societyillustrators.org/tim-obrien|website=Society of Illustrators|accessdate=2016-10-06}}</ref>\n*Honorary Doctorate Degree, 2013, Lyme Academy College of Fine Art<ref name=\"uarts\">{{cite web|title=Profile|url=http://www.uarts.edu/users/tobrien|website=University of the Arts|accessdate=2016-10-06}}</ref>\n*Commencement speech at Paier College of Art, 1996 and 2002<ref name=\"shapiro\" />\n* O'Brien's ''Time'' magazine covers are in the collection of the [[National Gallery of Art]], Washington, DC<ref name=\"NGA\" />\n*Chosen by ''Irish American Magazine'' as one of their 100 top Irish Americans, years 1999 and 2000<ref name=\"PCA\">{{cite web|last1=Smyser|first1=Kathy|title=Artist Spotlight|url=http://engage.pcad.edu/blog/artist-spotlight-tim-obrien-american-illustrator|website=Pennsylvania College of Art & Design|accessdate=2016-10-06}}</ref>\n*Awards from [[Society of Illustrators]] in New York and Los Angeles \u00b7 [[Graphis Inc.]] \u00b7 ''Print Magazine'' \u00b7 ''[[Communication Arts Magazine]]'' \u00b7 the Society of Publication Designers \u00b7 American Illustration \u00b7 Art Director's Club\n*In 2019, Tim O'Brien was awarded all 3 top illustration awards; Bronze, Silver and Gold, for covers of Donald Trump for [[Time Magazine]].<ref name=\"ArtDirectorsClub-Gold\">{{cite web|title=Gold Cube|url=https://www.oneclub.org/awards/adcawards/-award/32010/stormy|website=The One Club for Creativty|accessdate=2020-02-25}}</ref><ref name=\"ArtDirectorsClub-Silver\">{{cite web|title=Silver Cube|url=https://www.oneclub.org/awards/adcawards/-award/32011/in-deep|website=The One Club for Creativty|accessdate=2020-02-25}}</ref><ref name=\"ArtDirectorsClub-Bronze\">{{cite web|title=Bronze Cube|url=https://www.oneclub.org/awards/adcawards/-award/32009/king-me|website=The One Club for Creativty|accessdate=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n\n===Service===\n*Chairman of the Education Committee, [[Society of Illustrators]], New York (1996\u20132006).\n*Member of the Executive Committee, [[Society of Illustrators]], New York\n*Served on the Board of the Illustration Conference in 2003\n*President of the [[Society of Illustrators]], New York<ref name=\"uarts\" />\n*Chairman of 'Illustrators 49' at the [[Society of Illustrators]]\n*Chairman of the Scholarship Committee at the [[Society of Illustrators]]\n\n===Exhibitions===\n*Lyme Academy of Fine Arts, ''Portraits and Illustrations: A Retrospective'', 2013<ref name=\"LYME\">{{cite web|title=College Hosts Opening Reception for Exhibition by Famed Illustrator Tim O'Brien|url=http://www.lymeacademy.edu/index.php/about/news/college_hosts_opening_reception_for_exhibition_by_famed_illustrator_tim_obrien/|website=Lyme Academy College of Fine Arts|publisher=College of the University of New Haven|accessdate=2016-10-16}}</ref>\n*Norman Rockwell Museum, ''Rockwell and Realism in an Abstract World'', 2016 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrm.org/2016/06/rockwell-realism-abstract-world-2/ |title=Rockwell and Realism in an Abstract World - Norman Rockwell Museum - The Home for American Illustration |website=Nrm.org |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*Corpo Gallery [http://www.copronason.com/]\n\n==As an educator==\nO'Brien lectures frequently across the country.  His speaking engagements have included the Norman Rockwell Museum, the Society of Illustrators, Syracuse University, School of Visual Arts, Pratt Institute, Rhode Island School of Design, and California College of the Arts.<ref name=\"LYME\"/>\n*[[University of the Arts (Philadelphia)|University of the Arts]], Distinguished Adjunct Professor of Illustration, 1990 - 2016\n*[[Pratt Institute]], Adjunct Professor \u2013 Illustration, 2009 to present\n*[[Paier College of Art]] Adjunct Professor \u2013 Illustration, 1994 \u2013 1996<ref name=\"uarts\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nUp until 2004, O'Brien stayed active in the boxing world of his youth as a trainer.<ref name=\"nonslick\"/> Since 2006 O'Brien has run the [[New York City Marathon]], raising money for The Children's [[Inflammatory bowel disease|IBD]] Center at [[Mount Sinai Hospital (Manhattan)|Mount Sinai Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Running the NYC Marathon 2007|url=http://www.drawger.com/tonka/?article_id=3902|website=Drawger|accessdate=2016-10-16}}</ref>\n\nThe artist lives with his wife Elizabeth Parisi and son Cassius in [[Brooklyn, New York]]. O'Brien works from home out of his third floor studio.<ref name=\"shapiro\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://illoz.com/obrien Collection of the artists work] at illoz\n* [http://drawger.com/tonka/ Artists personal blog] at Drawger\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Obrien, Tim}}\n[[Category:American illustrators]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American magazine illustrators]]\n[[Category:Artists from New Haven, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century American painters]]\n[[Category:People from North Haven, Connecticut]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|others named Tim O'Brien|Tim O'Brien (disambiguation){{!}}Tim O'Brien}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name        = Tim O'Brien\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age |1964|11|16|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[New Haven, Connecticut]], U.S.\n| nationality   = American\n| training    = [[Paier College of Art]]\n| field  = [[illustration]], [[fine artist]]\n| awards        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Hamilton King Award]], 2009\n* Medals, Society of Illustrators, Graphis, The Art Directors Club, Society of Publication Designers\n}}\n| website = {{url|obrienillustration.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Tim O'Brien''' (born November 16, 1964) is an American artist who works in a [[Realism (arts)|realistic]] style.\n\nHis illustrations have appeared on the covers and interior pages of magazines such as ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', ''[[GQ]]'', ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', ''[[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]]'', ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', and many others. His illustrations are also used by the [[US Postal Service]] for [[postage stamps]].<ref name=\"uarts\" />\n\n==Early life and education==\nO'Brien's [[paternal]] grandparents came from Ireland, and his [[maternal]] grandparents from [[Norwich, Connecticut]], arriving in the United States from Quebec.<ref name=\"AIAP\" /> His grandfather became a caretaker at [[Yale University]].<ref name=\"shapiro\" />\n\nThe artist was the second of three boys in his family.<ref name=\"shapiro\" /> A youth officer suggested [[boxing]] and O'Brien took the advice and began training as a boxer in high school, going on to box as a [[Middleweight#Boxing|middleweight]] amateur in the [[Police Athletic League]].<ref name=\"shapiro\" /><ref name=\"nonslick\">{{cite web | first=Pete | last=Ryan | title=Tim O'Brien Interview | date=2010-03-29 | url =http://nonslick.blogspot.com/2010/03/tim-obrien.html |  accessdate = 2016-10-16 }}</ref> Although he drew and painted all during his youth, O'Brien thought that he would be a boxer.<ref name=\"shapiro\" />\n\nAt the age of 18, O'Brien gave up his ambitions of becoming a professional boxer and in the same year received a [[Pell Grant]] which he used to enroll in the [[Paier College of Art]],<ref name=\"shapiro\">{{cite news|last1=Shapiro|first1=Ellen|title=Tim O'Brien, Master Portrait Painter|url=http://buglogic.com/shapiro/Tim_O'Brien_Profile.html |accessdate=2016-10-17|issue=July\u2013August 2002|publisher=Communication Arts}}</ref> New Haven, CT.\n\nHe went on to graduate in 1987 with a [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] degree. His instructors at Paier included [[Leonard Everett Fisher]], [[Ken Davies (artist)|Ken Davies]] and Robert Zappalorti. While attending Paier, the young artist painted [[trompe l'oeil]] images for fun, which his instructors Ken Davies and Robert Zappalorti were also known to do, in which the viewer of the paintings are deceived into thinking they were seeing an actual object. In one such case, students attempted to use electrical outlets that O'Brien had painted on the wall.<ref name=\"shapiro\" /><ref name=\"North Haven News\" />\n\n===Artistic influences===\nIn grade school, O'Brien often visited the [[Yale University Art Gallery|Yale Art Gallery]].<ref name=\"shapiro\" /> O'Brien's favorite art works at this early age, which he was able to view at the Yale Gallery, were by [[Thomas Eakins]] and [[Paul Cadmus]], of which the young artist especially admired the detail and brushwork of Cadmus.<ref name=\"shapiro\" /> Other early influences for the artist were the 19th century Russian painter, [[Ivan Shishkin]], and British painter, [[Lord Leighton]].<ref name=\"lines and colors\">{{cite web|last1=Parker|first1=Charley|title=Tim O'Brien|url=http://linesandcolors.com/2006/09/15/tim-obrien/|website=Lines and Color|accessdate=2016-10-28}}</ref> Later influences for O'Brien include various contemporary artists such as [[Gottfried Helnwein]], [[George Tooker]] and [[Mark Tansey]], as well as illustrators such as [[Guy Billout]] and [[David Suter]].<ref name=\"AIAP\" />\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early===\nBefore graduation from Paier in 1987, O'Brien entered into what became a long relationship with the artists' representative [[Peter Lott]]. Lott had seen O'Brien's work at the [[Society of Illustrators]] Student Show.<ref name=\"shapiro\" />\n\nO'Brien started his illustration career primarily as a book cover artist<ref name=\"AIAP\">{{cite web|last1=Newman|first1=Robert|title=Illustrator Profile: Tim O'Brien|url=http://www.ai-ap.com/publications/article/13942/illustrator-profile-tim-obrien-focus-on-ideas.html|website=AI-IP|accessdate=2016-10-05}}</ref> and continues to work for book publishing houses, creating covers for such authors as [[Ray Bradbury]], [[Thomas Hardy]], [[Walter Dean Myers]] and many others.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tim O'Brien|url=https://www.librarything.com/author/obrientim-14&all=1|website=Library Thing|accessdate=2016-10-30}}</ref>\n\nThe artist credits his first big break as a ''Time'' Magazine cover done in 1989.<ref name=\"AIAP\" /> Even though O'Brien's contribution to the cover was only a painting of a small teardrop overlaid on a [[Gilbert Stewart]] portrait of [[George Washington]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Time Magazine, Oct 23 1989|url=http://content.time.com/time/covers/0,16641,19891023,00.html|website=Time Magazine|accessdate=2016-10-05}}</ref> it got him the attention of magazine art directors, and bigger assignments quickly followed.<ref name=\"AIAP\" /> O'Brien was called on again almost 20 years later to paint another teardrop on the cover of ''Time'', for the cover story \"The Price Of Greed\" following the onset of [[the great recession|a severe global financial recession]] in the September 29, 2008 issue of the magazine.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Price of Greed|url=http://content.time.com/time/covers/europe/0,16641,20080929,00.html|website=Time Magazine|accessdate=2016-10-05}}</ref>\n\n==Notable works==\n\n===Book covers===\n\nBetween 2008 and 2010, O'Brien was commissioned by [[Scholastic Publishing]] to illustrate each cover of ''[[The Hunger Games]]'' trilogy, by [[Suzanne Collins]], including ''The Hunger Games'' \"mockingjay\" logo. The images were then used again for promotional posters when the film distributor [[Lionsgate]] turned the best selling books into a film franchise.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Aronoff|first1=Amy|title=Professor Tim O'Brien Swept Up In Hunger Games Success As Logo Becomes Ubiquitous|url=http://gateway.pratt.edu/top-stories-apr-2012/2012/4/18/professor-tim-obrien-swept-up-in-hunger-games-success-as-log.html|website=Pratt|publisher=Pratt Institute|accessdate=2016-10-05}}</ref> At the end of the films official [[theatrical trailer]], the ring and bird by the artist are seen ablaze.\n\nO'Brien closely collaborated on the designs with his wife, Elizabeth Parisi, Creative Director for Scholastic, Inc.<ref name=\"NYDN\">{{cite web|last1=Weichselbaum|first1=Simone|title=Wings of love: 'Hunger Games' logo is brainchild of Brooklyn couple|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/wings-love-hunger-games-logo-brainchild-brooklyn-couple-article-1.1060947|website=New York Daily News|accessdate=2016-10-06}}</ref>\n\n===''Time'' covers===\nTime Magazine covers by the artist are in the [[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]] of the [[Smithsonian]]<ref name=\"NGA\">{{cite web|title=Time Magazine Collection|url=http://npg.si.edu/portraits/collection-highlights/time-magazine-highlights?page=8&edan_q=*%3A*&edan_fq%5B0%5D=date%3A%221990s%22&edan_fq%5B1%5D=online_media_type%3A%22Images%22|website=National Portrait Gallery|publisher=Smithsonian|accessdate=2016-10-06}}</ref>\n\nStarting in 1989, O'Brien worked with [[art director]], Arthur Hochstein, and created over a dozen covers for ''Time'' with him. Other art directors at Time that the artist has worked closely with are Joe Zeff and D.W. Pine.<ref name=\"spd\">{{cite web|last1=Newman|first1=Robert|title=The Time Covers of Arthur Hochstein, Pt. 1: Tim O'Brien|url=http://www.spd.org/2010/10/the.php|website=Society of Publication Designers|accessdate=2016-10-11}}</ref>\n\nO'Brien occasionally creates cover illustrations for ''Time'' Magazine that are a possibility for publication but never used, as was the case with his ''[[Time Person of the Year|Person of the Year]]'' (2007) portrait, in which the artist was commissioned to paint [[Vladimir Putin]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stengal|first1=Richard|title=The Covers You Don't See|url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/2007/article/0,28804,1699115_1699118_1699122,00.html?iid=sr-link5|website=Time Magazine|accessdate=2016-10-05}}</ref> Putin was selected as \"person of the year\" by ''Time'' in 2007, however the final image the magazine selected was a photograph by [[Platon (photographer)|Platon]].\n\nO'Brien's ''The End of Bin Laden'' cover, which the artist created in 2002 when editors at ''Time'' believed the [[Osama bin Laden|al-Qaeda leader]] was trapped and was or would soon be dead in Afghanistan,<ref name=\"North Haven News\" /> was not published until nine years later in the May 20, 2011 issue.<ref name=\"AIAP\" /> In the case of ''The End of Bin Laden'' cover image, O'Brien employed a concept that had been used much earlier by ''Time'' in which is a red X is painted over the portrait. The first time this concept was used was for Adolf Hitler in the May 7, 1945 issue of the magazine, before Hitler's body was discovered.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gustini|first1=Ray|title=A Brief History of Time Magazine's X Covers|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2011/05/brief-history-time-magazine-red-x-covers/350228/|website=The Atlantic|accessdate=2016-11-02}}</ref> O'Brien had used the same red X approach for an earlier ''Time'' cover, ''The Death of Abu Mousab al-Zarqawi'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/covers/0,16641,20060619,00.html |title=TIME Magazine Cover: The Death of Abu Mousab al-Zarqawi - June 19, 2006 - Iraq - Al-Qaeda - Terrorism |publisher=Content.time.com |date=2006-06-19 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref> for the June 19, 2006 issue of the magazine.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rothman|first1=Lily|title=Behind the Osama bin Laden 'Red X' TIME Cover|url=http://time.com/4307301/5-years-osama-bin-laden/|website=Time Magazine|accessdate=2016-11-02}}</ref>\nAs of 2020, Tim O'Brien has had over 30 Time covers published.\nListed below are a selection of notable works for ''Time'' by the artist.\n\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n*September 4, 1996 ''The Choice''<ref>{{cite web|author=posted by Robert Newman |url=http://www.spd.org/2010/10/the.php |title=The Time Covers of Arthur Hochstein, Pt. 1: Tim O'Brien - Grids - SPD.ORG - Grids |publisher=Spd.Org |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*December 28, 1998 ''Men of the Year, Kenneth Star and Bill Clinton''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/covers/0,16641,19981228,00.html |title=TIME Magazine Cover: Kenneth Starr & Bill Clinton, Men of the Year - Dec. 28, 1998 - Bill Clinton - Kenneth Starr - Person of the Year - U.S. Presidents - Scandals |publisher=Content.time.com |date=1998-12-28 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*March 10, 2003 ''Life After Saddam''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/covers/0,16641,20030310,00.html |title=TIME Magazine Cover: Saddam Hussein - Mar. 10, 2003 - Saddam Hussein - Iraq - Middle East |publisher=Content.time.com |date=2003-03-10 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*November 10, 2008 ''The Choice''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/0,9263,7601081110,00.html |title=TIME Magazine - U.S. Edition - November 10, 2008 Vol. 172 No. 19 |publisher=Content.time.com |date=2008-11-10 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n{{Col-2}}\n*June 7, 2010 ''Why Being Pope Means Never Having to Say You're Sorry''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/pacific/0,9263,503100607,00.html |title=TIME Magazine - South Pacific Edition - June 7, 2010 No. 22 |publisher=Content.time.com |date=2010-06-07 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*December 20, 2010 ''Palin in Progress''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/covers/0,16641,20101220,00.html |title=TIME Magazine Cover: Palin in Progress - Dec. 20, 2010 - Sarah Palin - Republicans - Politics |publisher=Content.time.com |date=2010-12-20 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*May 20, 2011 ''The End of Bin Laden''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/covers/0,16641,20110520,00.html |title=TIME Magazine Cover: The End of Bin Laden - May 20, 2011 - Al-Qaeda - Osama bin Laden - Terrorism - Special Issues |publisher=Content.time.com |date=2011-05-20 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*September 5, 2011 ''The World After Gaddafi''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/0,9263,7601110905,00.html?iid=sr-link7 |title=TIME Magazine - U.S. Edition - September 5, 2011 Vol. 178 No. 9 |publisher=Content.time.com |date=2011-09-05 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n{{Col-end}}\n\n===''Rolling Stone''===\nO'Brien illustrated portraits of [[The Police]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Stone |first=Rolling |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/100-greatest-artists-of-all-time-19691231/the-police-20110420 |title=The Police &#124; 100 Greatest Artists |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=2010-12-02 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref> [[Michael Jackson]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://illoz.com/obrien/?section=portfolios&gallery_id=12&image_id=19933&search_id=2015&search_type=image |title=Tim O'Brien - Portraits and Illustrations |publisher=Illoz.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref> [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Stone |first=Rolling |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/100-greatest-artists-of-all-time-19691231/nirvana-20110926 |title=Nirvana &#124; 100 Greatest Artists |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=2010-12-02 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref> and [[Little Richard]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://illoz.com/obrien/?section=portfolios&gallery_id=12&image_id=395&search_id=10365 |title=Tim O'Brien - Portraits and Illustrations |publisher=Illoz.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref> in ''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s 100 Greatest Artists of All Time<ref>{{cite web|title=Rolling Stone: The 100 Greatest Artists of All Time|url=http://www.spd.org/2011/04/rolling-stone-the-100-greatest.php|website=Society of Publication Designers|accessdate=2016-10-06}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, O'Brien said the work he was most proud of was his 2008 cover illustration for ''Rolling Stone'' in which the magazine endorsed candidate Barack Obama for President.<ref name=\"NYDN\" /> The cover, which depicted the future President with a halo-like glow around him, created a mild controversy, with critics of the image saying it [[deification|deified]] the candidate.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Powell|first1=Michael Orion|title=The Deification of Obama|url=http://mopowell.blogspot.com/2008/03/deification-of-obama.html|accessdate=2016-10-30}}</ref>\n\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n'''Covers'''\n*March 2008 Cover, ''Barack Obama, A New Hope''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/coverwall/2008#1048 |title=2008 Magazine Archives |publisher=Rolling Stone |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*January 2009 Cover, ''Bush Apologizes''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/coverwall/2009#1070 |title=2009 Magazine Archives |publisher=Rolling Stone |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*February 2012 Cover, ''The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/coverwall/2012#1149 |title=2012 Magazine Archives |publisher=Rolling Stone |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n{{Col-2}}\n'''Page illustrations'''\n*''Al Gore:The Revolution is beginning'', June 28, 2007<ref>{{cite web|last=Bates |first=Eric |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/al-gore-the-revolution-is-beginning-20070628 |title=Al Gore's Movement to Stop Global Warming: 'The Revolution Is Beginning' |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=2007-06-28 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*''Beck'', March 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theispot.com/whatsnew/2014/3/tim-o-brien-beck-for-rolling-stone.htm |title=Tim O\u2019Brien: Beck for Rolling Stone |publisher=Theispot.com |date=2014-03-04 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n{{Col-end}}\n\n===''Mother Jones''===\nFor the December 2012 release, the magazine printed double covers, in which one cover was sent to [[subscribers]] of the magazine and the alternate cover was shown on [[newsstand]]s. O'Brien illustrated both covers, and in very different stylistic ways.<ref>{{cite web|author=Robert Newman |url=http://www.foliomag.com/behind-mother-jones-s-recent-dual-cover-strategy/#.UHxWIBh5nV0 |title=Behind Mother Jones\u2019s Recent Dual Cover Strategy - Folio: |publisher=Foliomag.com |date=2012-10-12 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref> For the cover that went to newsstands, titled ''Sugar Kills'', the artist created a surreal vignette of a glass pitcher as a human skull, and for the version delivered to subscribers, titled ''Solitary in Iran'', O'Brien painted a lonely jail cell with a single occupant. That both covers were illustrated by O'Brien was more by chance than design. The ''Mother Jones'' creative director Tim J. Luddy first completed conceptual sketches for both covers and after doing so, decided O'Brien was the best choice for both.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Newman|first1=Robert|title=Behind Mother Jones's Recent Dual Cover Strategy|url=http://www.foliomag.com/behind-mother-jones-s-recent-dual-cover-strategy/#.UHxWIBh5nV0|website=Folio|accessdate=2016-10-06}}</ref>\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n'''Covers'''\n*February 2008 ''The Last Empire''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://drawger.com/tonka/?article_id=4998 |title=Tim OBrien - The Last Empire |publisher=Drawger.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*September 2010, ''The BP Coverup''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/environment/2010/09/bp-ocean-cover-up |title=The BP Cover-Up \u2013 Mother Jones |publisher=Motherjones.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*March 2011, ''The Vampire Economy''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coverjunkie.com/new-covers/4651 |title=Coverjunkie |publisher=Coverjunkie |date=2016-10-31 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*July 2013, ''Gagged by Big Ag''<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.spd.org/2013/11/mother-jones-covers-designed-b.php |title=\"Namaste\" to Tim J Luddy of Mother Jones - Grids - SPD.ORG - Grids |publisher=Spd.Org |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*\n{{Col-2}}\n'''Page illustrations'''\n*''Harpy, Hero, Heretic: Hillary'', January 2007<ref>{{cite web|author=Jack Hitt |url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2007/01/harpy-hero-heretic-hillary |title=Harpy, Hero, Heretic: Hillary \u2013 Mother Jones |publisher=Motherjones.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n{{Col-end}}\n\n===Magazine work===\nO'Brien magazine covers have received numerous awards and citations including ''Cover of the Day'' by the Society of Publication Designers. Below are listed a small sample of noted cover illustrations by the artist.\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n*''[[The Atlantic]]'', April 2001, ''The Next Ruling Class''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/past/docs/issues/2001/04/bgcover.htm |title=Apr 2001 &#124; Cover Art &#124; O'Brien |publisher=The Atlantic |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*[[Smithsonian (magazine)|''Smithsonian'']], March 2012, ''100th Anniversary of The Titantic''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theispot.com/whatsnew/2012/4/tim-o-brien-the-titanic-for-smithsonian.htm |title=Tim O\u2019Brien: The Titanic for Smithsonian |publisher=Theispot.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', March 2011, ''Roger Goodell Throne of Games''<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.spd.org/2013/03/cover-of-the-day-friday-editio-38.php |title=Cover of the Day: Friday Edition - Grids - SPD.ORG - Grids |publisher=Spd.Org |date=2013-03-11 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n{{Col-2}}\n*''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', May 16, 2016, ''Vin Scully''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidesocal.com/dodgers/2016/05/10/vin-scully-is-sports-illustrateds-latest-cover-boy/ |title=Vin Scully is Sports Illustrated\u2019s latest cover boy. &#124; Inside the Dodgers |publisher=Insidesocal.com |date=2016-05-10 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*''[[GQ]]'', July 2015, ''Who is Mitt Romney?''<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.gq.com/story/mitt-romney-wells-tower-gq-august-2012 |title=Mitt Romney: Desperately Seeking Mitt |publisher=GQ |date=2012-07-24 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*''[[GQ]]'', January 2016, ''What Would Cool Jesus Do?''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theispot.com/whatsnew/2016/1/tim-o-brien-illustration-cool-jesus.htm |title=Tim O\u2019Brien Illustration: Cool Jesus |publisher=Theispot.com |date=2016-01-06 |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n{{Col-end}}\n\n===Postage stamps===\nO'Brien's work first appeared on [[Postage stamps and postal history of the United States|U.S. postage stamps]] in 2006. The artist was commissioned to portray [[Hattie McDaniel]] as part of the U.S. Postal Services Black Heritage stamp series.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hattie McDaniel|url=http://postalmuseum.si.edu/tt/artwork/25/|website=Postal Museum|accessdate=2016-10-30}}</ref> The choice of the actress to be featured in this series of stamps which had included prominent figures in [[civil rights]] history such as [[Harriet Tubman]] and [[Martin Luther King, Jr]] caused some to voice concerns<ref>{{cite web|last1=Washington|first1=Robin|title=A Hattie McDaniel U.S. Mail Stamp?|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5306369|website=NPR News|publisher=National Public Radio|accessdate=2016-10-30}}</ref> The U.S. Postal Service defended their decision by noting that the actress was the first African American to Win an [[Academy Award]] as well as a being an influential civil rights advocate during the 1940s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hattie McDaniel|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/hattie-mcdaniel-first-african-american-to-win-an-academy-awardr-featured-on-new-39-cent-postage-stamp-55101272.html|website=PR NewsWire|publisher=US Postal Service|accessdate=2016-10-30}}</ref>\n\nUS postage stamps by O'Brien that followed:\n*[[Judy Garland]], 2006<ref>{{cite web|url=http://postalmuseum.si.edu/tt/artwork/21/ |title=Artwork - Trailblazers and Trendsetters - Art of the Stamp |publisher=Postalmuseum.si.edu |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*[[Danny Thomas]], 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=http://about.usps.com/postal-bulletin/2012/pb22328/html/info_026.htm |title=Stamp Announcement 12-18: Danny Thomas |publisher=About.usps.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*[[Shirley Temple]], 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=https://about.usps.com/news/national-releases/2016/pr16_027.htm |title=Shirley Temple Becomes the 20th Inductee in the Legends of Hollywood Stamp Series |publisher=About.usps.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*[[Father Theodore Hesburgh]], 2017 release<ref>{{cite web|url=http://about.usps.com/news/national-releases/2016/pr16_072.htm |title=USPS previews 2017 stamps |publisher=About.usps.com |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n\n==Working process==\nO'Brien begins with a detailed drawing on [[gesso|gessoed panel]], working on [[Sepia (color)|sepia]] or grey half tone and drawing with pencil, charcoal pencil, colored pencil, [[gouache]]. When this is completed the artist uses an [[airbrush]] to even tones and set the key of the artwork and add light and dark to areas. Then an [[Acrylic paint|acrylic]] coat is applied to the drawing and finally painted over in thin layers of oil.<ref name=\"modern met\">{{cite web|last1=Hosmer|first1=Katie|title=Incredibly Surreal Illustrations by Tim O'Brien|url=http://www.mymodernmet.com/profiles/blogs/tim-o-brien-conceptual-illustrations|website=My Modern Met|accessdate=2016-10-06}}</ref> Although the artist began illustrating well before personal computers were able to render complex images, some of his concept images are currently rendered using computer software.<ref name=\"AIAP\" />\n\n===Deadlines===\nThe turn-around time between an illustration being commissioned by a weekly magazine such as ''Time'' is often less than 48 hours from concept sketch to final art for the artist. During this time, the sketch or draft of the idea is the most demanding.<ref name=\"North Haven News\">{{cite web|last1=Bellmore|first1=Miichael|title=North Haven native works quietly, but images stay with us forever|url=http://www.nhregister.com/article/NH/20130202/NEWS/302029964|website=New Haven Register|accessdate=2016-10-17}}</ref>\n\nArthur Hockstein, art director at ''Time'' Magazine from 1994 through 2009<ref>{{cite web|last1=Newman|first1=Robert|title=Arthur Hochstein's 15 Favorite Time Magazine Covers|url=http://www.spd.org/2010/08/arthur-hochsteins-time-magazin.php|website=Society of Publication Designers|accessdate=2016-10-30}}</ref> said of O'Brien that the magazine staff was amazed at the intricacy and draftsmanship of O'Brien's work, delivered under such short deadlines.<ref name=\"shapiro\" /> Robert Newman, former Design Director at [[Entertainment Weekly]] recounted the paintings still being wet, delivered in specially constructed boxes containing the art by O'Brien and the smell of oil paint filling the room as the work was opened just before [[time unit|deadline]].<ref name=\"AIAP\" />\n\n===Creative process===\nO'Brien has said that he thinks of his paintings as one frame movies and his job as illustrator is to direct the viewer to see the idea when he wants them to see it.<ref name=\"The Day\">{{cite web|last1=Koster|first1=Rick|title=Illustrator Tim O'Brien to visit LACFA|url=http://www.theday.com/article/20131017/ENT16/310179606/-1/rss05|website=The Day|accessdate=2016-10-17}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview conducted by The Illustrators Guild of Ireland in 2002, O'Brien described his style by saying, \"My description is conceptual realism with a leaning toward the slightly idealized.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.illustratorsireland.com/index.php/features/fullstory/tim_obrien_interview/ |title=Illustrators Ireland: Features |accessdate=2008-05-17 |last=Byrne |first=Tom |date=2002-03-29 |work=Illustrators Guild of Ireland |publisher=Illustrators Ireland }}</ref>\n\n==Honors and service==\n\n===Honors===\nOn April 26, 2016 O'Brien spoke at the United Nations in New York City at the invitation of [[World Intellectual Property Organization|The World Intellectual Property Organization]], during which the artist's work were shown. He discussed [[commercial art]] and [[Intellectual property#Copyright infringement|intellectual property rights]] in a digital world and how technology is having both advantageous and troubling consequences on both.<ref name=\"UN\">{{cite web|title=Tim O'Brien Speaks at the United Nations on a pane;; titled ''Digital Creativity: Reimagining Culture For Sustainable Development''|url=https://altpick.com/news/10317|website=Alternative Pick|accessdate=2016-10-16}}</ref>\n* [[Hamilton King Award]], [[Society of Illustrators]] (2009)<ref name=\"soi\">{{cite web|title=Hamilton King 2009|url=https://www.societyillustrators.org/tim-obrien|website=Society of Illustrators|accessdate=2016-10-06}}</ref>\n*Honorary Doctorate Degree, 2013, Lyme Academy College of Fine Art<ref name=\"uarts\">{{cite web|title=Profile|url=http://www.uarts.edu/users/tobrien|website=University of the Arts|accessdate=2016-10-06}}</ref>\n*Commencement speech at Paier College of Art, 1996 and 2002<ref name=\"shapiro\" />\n* O'Brien's ''Time'' magazine covers are in the collection of the [[National Gallery of Art]], Washington, DC<ref name=\"NGA\" />\n*Chosen by ''Irish American Magazine'' as one of their 100 top Irish Americans, years 1999 and 2000<ref name=\"PCA\">{{cite web|last1=Smyser|first1=Kathy|title=Artist Spotlight|url=http://engage.pcad.edu/blog/artist-spotlight-tim-obrien-american-illustrator|website=Pennsylvania College of Art & Design|accessdate=2016-10-06}}</ref>\n*Awards from [[Society of Illustrators]] in New York and Los Angeles \u00b7 [[Graphis Inc.]] \u00b7 ''Print Magazine'' \u00b7 ''[[Communication Arts Magazine]]'' \u00b7 the Society of Publication Designers \u00b7 American Illustration \u00b7 Art Director's Club\n*In 2019, Tim O'Brien was awarded all 3 top illustration awards; Bronze, Silver and Gold, for covers of Donald Trump for [[Time Magazine]].<ref name=\"ArtDirectorsClub\">{{cite web|title=Gold Cube|url=https://www.oneclub.org/awards/adcawards/-award/32010/stormy|website=The One Club for Creativty|accessdate=2020-02-25}}</ref><ref name=\"ArtDirectorsClub\">{{cite web|title=Silber Cube|url=https://www.oneclub.org/awards/adcawards/-award/32011/in-deep|website=The One Club for Creativty|accessdate=2020-02-25}}</ref><ref name=\"ArtDirectorsClub\">{{cite web|title=Bronze Cube|url=https://www.oneclub.org/awards/adcawards/-award/32009/king-me|website=The One Club for Creativty|accessdate=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n\n===Service===\n*Chairman of the Education Committee, [[Society of Illustrators]], New York (1996\u20132006).\n*Member of the Executive Committee, [[Society of Illustrators]], New York\n*Served on the Board of the Illustration Conference in 2003\n*President of the [[Society of Illustrators]], New York<ref name=\"uarts\" />\n*Chairman of 'Illustrators 49' at the [[Society of Illustrators]]\n*Chairman of the Scholarship Committee at the [[Society of Illustrators]]\n\n===Exhibitions===\n*Lyme Academy of Fine Arts, ''Portraits and Illustrations: A Retrospective'', 2013<ref name=\"LYME\">{{cite web|title=College Hosts Opening Reception for Exhibition by Famed Illustrator Tim O'Brien|url=http://www.lymeacademy.edu/index.php/about/news/college_hosts_opening_reception_for_exhibition_by_famed_illustrator_tim_obrien/|website=Lyme Academy College of Fine Arts|publisher=College of the University of New Haven|accessdate=2016-10-16}}</ref>\n*Norman Rockwell Museum, ''Rockwell and Realism in an Abstract World'', 2016 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrm.org/2016/06/rockwell-realism-abstract-world-2/ |title=Rockwell and Realism in an Abstract World - Norman Rockwell Museum - The Home for American Illustration |website=Nrm.org |date= |accessdate=2017-06-17}}</ref>\n*Corpo Gallery [http://www.copronason.com/]\n\n==As an educator==\nO'Brien lectures frequently across the country.  His speaking engagements have included the Norman Rockwell Museum, the Society of Illustrators, Syracuse University, School of Visual Arts, Pratt Institute, Rhode Island School of Design, and California College of the Arts.<ref name=\"LYME\"/>\n*[[University of the Arts (Philadelphia)|University of the Arts]], Distinguished Adjunct Professor of Illustration, 1990 - 2016\n*[[Pratt Institute]], Adjunct Professor \u2013 Illustration, 2009 to present\n*[[Paier College of Art]] Adjunct Professor \u2013 Illustration, 1994 \u2013 1996<ref name=\"uarts\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nUp until 2004, O'Brien stayed active in the boxing world of his youth as a trainer.<ref name=\"nonslick\"/> Since 2006 O'Brien has run the [[New York City Marathon]], raising money for The Children's [[Inflammatory bowel disease|IBD]] Center at [[Mount Sinai Hospital (Manhattan)|Mount Sinai Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Running the NYC Marathon 2007|url=http://www.drawger.com/tonka/?article_id=3902|website=Drawger|accessdate=2016-10-16}}</ref>\n\nThe artist lives with his wife Elizabeth Parisi and son Cassius in [[Brooklyn, New York]]. O'Brien works from home out of his third floor studio.<ref name=\"shapiro\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://illoz.com/obrien Collection of the artists work] at illoz\n* [http://drawger.com/tonka/ Artists personal blog] at Drawger\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Obrien, Tim}}\n[[Category:American illustrators]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American magazine illustrators]]\n[[Category:Artists from New Haven, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century American painters]]\n[[Category:People from North Haven, Connecticut]]\n", "name_user": "Quebec99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix duplicate ref names \u2013You can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tim_O%27Brien_(illustrator)"}
{"title_page": "Moufida Tlatli", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|imagesize      = \n|name           = Moufida Tlatli\n|birth_date     = {{birth year and age|1947}}\n|birth_place = [[Sidi Bou Sa\u00efd]], [[French Tunisia]]\n|occupation  = Film director, film editor, politician\n|yearsactive = 1970\u2013present \n}}\n'''Moufida Tlatli''' ({{lang-aeb|\u0645\u0641\u064a\u062f\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0644\u0627\u062a\u0644\u064a}}; born 1947) is a [[Tunisia]]n film director. She was the first Arab woman to direct a full feature-length film (''[[The Silences of the Palace]]'') in the [[Arab World]].\n\n== Biography ==\nShe was born in Sidi Bou Sa\u00efd suburb of the capital [[Tunis]] in 1947. She said that she discovered her love to cinema with the help of her philosophy teacher.\n\nAfter graduating from the French ''[[Institut des hautes \u00e9tudes cin\u00e9matographiques]]'' in 1968, she returned to Tunisia where she worked as a film editor for different [[Culture of Tunisia#Cinema|Tunisian films]].\n\nShe directed her first featured-film [[The Silences of the Palace]] in 1994. The film was acclaimed critically and won several awards : Cannes Film Festival's Golden Camera, the Golden Tanit of Carthage, British Film Institute Awards' Sutherland Trophy, Toronto Film Festival's International Critics' Award and Istanbul International Film Festival's Golden Tulip.\n\nHer second film, ''[[The Season of Men]]'', was screened in the [[Un Certain Regard]] section at the [[2000 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/5119/year/2000.html |title=Festival de Cannes: The Season of Men |accessdate=2009-10-15|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[2010\u20132011 Tunisian protests|downfall]] of president [[Zine El Abidine Ben Ali]] in 2011 she was appointed Minister of Culture in the provisional government.<ref>http://www.liberation.fr/monde/01012314313-tunisie-une-transition-a-hauts-risques</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n== Editor ==\n* [[1972]] : ''[[In The Land of Trannani]]''\n* [[1974]] : ''[[Sajn\u00e8ne]]''\n* [[1974]] : ''[[A People's Victory]]''\n* [[1975]] : ''[[Fatma 75]]''\n* [[1977]] : ''[[Omar Katlato]]''\n* [[1978]] : ''[[A Ball and Dreams]]''\n* [[1979]] : ''[[Nahla]]''\n* [[1980]] : ''[[Aziza]]''\n* [[1982]] : ''[[Shadows of The Earth]]''\n* [[1983]] : ''[[Crossings]]''\n* [[1984]] : ''[[Wonderers of The Desert]]''\n* [[1986]] : ''[[Arab]]''\n* [[1987]] : ''[[Arab Camera]]''\n* [[1988]] : ''[[The Trace]]''\n* [[1989]] : ''[[Leila's My Reason]]''\n* [[1990]] : ''[[The Song of The Rock]]''\n* [[1990]] : ''[[Halfaouine: Boy of the Terraces]]''\n* [[1992]] : ''[[The Wave's Hipsters]]''\n* [[1994]] : ''[[The Fire Dance]]''\n* [[1994]] : ''[[The Silences of the Palace]]''\n* [[2000]] : ''[[The Season of Men]]''\n* [[2004]] : ''[[Nadia and Sarra]]''\n\n==Director==\n* [[1994]] : ''[[The Silence of The Palaces]]''\n* [[2000]] : ''[[The Men's Season]]''\n* [[2004]] : ''[[Nadia and Sarah]]''\n\n==Writer==\n* [[1994]] : ''[[The Silence of The Palaces]]''\n* [[2000]] : ''[[The Men's Season]]''\n* [[2004]] : ''[[Nadia and Sarra]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tlatli, Moufida}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Tunisian film directors]]\n[[Category:Tunisian women film directors]]\n[[Category:Tunisian women]]\n\n{{Tunisia-film-director-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|imagesize      = \n|name           = Moufida Tlatli\n|birth_date     = {{birth year and age|1947}}\n|birth_place = [[Sidi Bou Sa\u00efd]], [[French Tunisia]]\n|occupation  = Film director, film editor, politician\n|yearsactive = 1970\u2013present \n}}\n'''Moufida Tlatli''' ({{lang-aeb|\u0645\u0641\u064a\u062f\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0644\u0627\u062a\u0644\u064a}}; born 1947) is a [[Tunisia]]n film director. She was the first Arab woman to direct a full feature-length film (''[[The Silences of the Palace]]'') in the [[Arab World]].\n\n== Biography ==\nShe was born in Sidi Bou Sa\u00efd suburb of the capital [[Tunis]] in 1947. She said that she discovered her love to cinema with the help of her philosophy teacher.\n\nAfter graduating from the French ''[[Institut des hautes \u00e9tudes cin\u00e9matographiques]]'' in 1968, she returned to Tunisia where she worked as a film editor for different [[Culture of Tunisia#Cinema|Tunisian films]].\n\nShe directed her first featured-film [[The Silences of the Palace]] in 1994. The film was acclaimed critically and won several awards : Cannes Film Festival's Golden Camera, the Golden Tanit of Carthage, British Film Institute Awards' Sutherland Trophy, Toronto Film Festival's International Critics' Award and Istanbul International Film Festival's Golden Tulip.\n\nHer second film, ''[[The Season of Men]]'', was screened in the [[Un Certain Regard]] section at the [[2000 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/5119/year/2000.html |title=Festival de Cannes: The Season of Men |accessdate=2009-10-15|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[2010\u20132011 Tunisian protests|downfall]] of president [[Zine El Abidine Ben Ali]] in 2011 she was appointed Minister of Culture in the provisional government.<ref>http://www.liberation.fr/monde/01012314313-tunisie-une-transition-a-hauts-risques</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n== Editor ==\n* [[1972]] : ''[[In The Land of Trannani]]''\n* [[1974]] : ''[[Sajn\u00e8ne]]''\n* [[1974]] : ''[[A People's Victory]]''\n* [[1975]] : ''[[Fatma 75]]''\n* [[1977]] : ''[[Omar Katlato]]''\n* [[1978]] : ''[[A Ball and Dreams]]''\n* [[1979]] : ''[[Nahla]]''\n* [[1980]] : ''[[Aziza]]''\n* [[1982]] : ''[[Shadows of The Earth]]''\n* [[1983]] : ''[[Crossings]]''\n* [[1984]] : ''[[Wonderers of The Desert]]''\n* [[1986]] : ''[[Arab]]''\n* [[1987]] : ''[[Arab Camera]]''\n* [[1988]] : ''[[The Trace]]''\n* [[1989]] : ''[[Leila's My Reason]]''\n* [[1990]] : ''[[The Song of The Rock]]''\n* [[1990]] : ''[[Halfaouine: Boy of the Terraces]]''\n* [[1992]] : ''[[The Wave's Hipsters]]''\n* [[1994]] : ''[[The Fire Dance]]''\n* [[1994]] : ''[[The Silences of the Palace]]''\n* [[2000]] : ''[[The Season of Men]]''\n* [[2004]] : ''[[Nadia and Sarra]]''\n\n==Director==\n* [[1994]] : ''[[The Silence of The Palaces]]''\n* [[2000]] : ''[[The Men's Season]]''\n* [[2004]] : ''[[Nadia and Sarah]]''\n\n==Writer==\n* [[1979]] : ''[[Aziza]]''\n* [[1994]] : ''[[The Seasons of The Palaces]]''\n* [[2000]] : ''[[The Men's Season]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tlatli, Moufida}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Tunisian film directors]]\n[[Category:Tunisian women film directors]]\n[[Category:Tunisian women]]\n\n{{Tunisia-film-director-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Nesrine1984", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWriter", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moufida_Tlatli"}
